{"title_page": "George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal.jpg|right|thumb|The 5th Earl Marischal, painted by [[Cosmo Alexander]]]]\n\n'''George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal''' (c. 1553\u20131623) was a [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scottish]] nobleman and [[Earl Marischal]]. He succeeded as earl on 7 October 1581, upon the death of his grandfather, [[William Keith, 4th Earl Marischal]].\n\nGeorge Keith was the son of William Keith, Master of Marischal and his wife Elizabeth Hay. Few details of his education are known, but in 1573 he went to Paris to study horsemanship, and during his travels lodged with [[Theodore Beza]] in Geneva where his younger brother William was killed by Spanish bandits. He returned to Scotland in 1580 when James VI made a northern progress and held a meeting of the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] at [[Dunnotar Castle]] on 18 June 1580. In October he was made a Gentleman of the King's Bedchamber.<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), pp. 23-5.</ref>\n\nDescribed as one of the most important and powerful men of his day in [[Scotland]], he was sent as [[ambassador]] to [[Denmark]] in June 1589 to negotiate the marriage of King [[James I of England|James VI of Scotland]] to [[Anne of Denmark]]. His companions were [[Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall]], James Scrimgeour Constable of Dundee, [[John Skene, Lord Curriehill|John Skene]], [[William Fowler (makar)|William Fowler]], and [[George Young (diplomat)|George Young]].<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), pp. 47-9.</ref> \n\nHe took part in a wedding ceremony at [[Kronborg]] on 20 August 1589 which involved him sitting on Anne of Denmark's bed as a proxy for the king.<ref>David Chrytraeus, ''Epistolae'' (Hanovia, 1614), pp. 696, 711: David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 22-3, 85-6: Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 50.</ref>\n\nHe founded the [[Marischal College]] in [[Aberdeen]] in 1593 and was [[Lord High Commissioner to the Parliament of Scotland|Royal commissioner]] to the [[Parliament of Scotland]] in 1609.\n\nHe rebuilt his [[family seat]] of [[Keith Marischal]] in 1589, and also constructed new buildings at Dunnottar Castle. He also built new harbours at [[Peterhead]] and [[Stonehaven]], using Norwegian timber and employing the mason James Mackene. The earl had a fishing boat and house at [[Footdee]] in Aberdeen, as well as a townhouse between the Tolbooth and the Quay.<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), pp. 152-157.</ref> Other houses included \"Gubriell\" near Dunfermline.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 749.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe married firstly (c. Feb. 1581) Margaret, the daughter of [[Alexander Home, 5th Lord Home]], by whom he had:\n\n*[[William Keith, 6th Earl Marischal|William, 6th Earl Marischal]].\n*Anne who married [[William Douglas, 7th Earl of Morton]].\n*Margaret who married (as his 1st wife) [[Robert Arbuthnot, 1st Viscount of Arbuthnott|Sir Robert Arbuthnott, of that ilk]] but had no issue.\n*Mary Keith married John Campbell of Cawdor\n\nHe married secondly (c. 1599), Margaret daughter of James Ogilvy, 6th [[Earl of Airlie|Lord Ogilvy of Airlie]], by whom he had:\n\n*James Keith of Benholm who had no male issue.\n*John Keith who had no issue.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*''A Genealogical History of the Dormant, Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire'', Sir Bernard Burke, 1883.\n*{{ODNBweb|id=15263|title=Keith, George, fourth Earl Marischal}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|sc}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lord High Commissioner to the Parliament of Scotland|Lord High Commissioner]]|years=1609\u20131617|before=[[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|The Duke of Lennox]]|after=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|The Marquess of Hamilton]]}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box | before=[[William Keith, 4th Earl Marischal|William Keith]] | title=[[Earl Marischal]] | after=[[William Keith, 6th Earl Marischal|William Keith]] | years=1581\u20131623}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marischal, George Keith, 5th Earl}}\n[[Category:1623 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Scotland to Denmark]]\n[[Category:Earls Marischal]]\n[[Category:Founders of Scottish schools and colleges]]\n[[Category:Lords High Commissioner to the Parliament of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Aberdeen]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal.jpg|right|thumb|The 5th Earl Marischal, painted by [[Cosmo Alexander]]]]\n\n'''George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal''' (c. 1553\u20131623) was a [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scottish]] nobleman and [[Earl Marischal]]. He succeeded as earl on 7 October 1581, upon the death of his grandfather, [[William Keith, 4th Earl Marischal]].\n\nGeorge Keith was the son of William Keith, Master of Marischal and his wife Elizabeth Hay. Few details of his education are known, but in 1573 he went to Paris to study horsemanship, and during his travels lodged with [[Theodore Beza]] in Geneva where his younger brother William was killed by Spanish bandits. He returned to Scotland in 1580 when James VI made a northern progress and held a meeting of the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] at [[Dunnotar Castle]] on 18 June 1580. In October he was made a Gentleman of the King's Bedchamber.<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), pp. 23-5.</ref>\n\nDescribed as one of the most important and powerful men of his day in [[Scotland]], he was sent as [[ambassador]] to [[Denmark]] in June 1589 to negotiate the marriage of King [[James I of England|James VI of Scotland]] to [[Anne of Denmark]]. His companions were [[Andrew Keith, Lord Dingwall]], James Scrimgeour Constable of Dundee, [[John Skene, Lord Curriehill|John Skene]], [[William Fowler (makar)|William Fowler]], and [[George Young (diplomat)|George Young]].<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), pp. 47-9.</ref> \n\nHe took part in a wedding ceremony at [[Kronborg]] on 20 August 1589 which involved him sitting on Anne of Denmark's bed as a proxy for the king.<ref>David Chrytraeus, ''Epistolae'' (Hanovia, 1614), pp. 696, 711: David Stevenson, ''Scotland's Last Royal Wedding'' (Edinburgh, 1997), pp. 22-3, 85-6: Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), p. 50.</ref>\n\nHe founded the [[Marischal College]] in [[Aberdeen]] in 1593 and was [[Lord High Commissioner to the Parliament of Scotland|Royal commissioner]] to the [[Parliament of Scotland]] in 1609.\n\nHe rebuilt his [[family seat]] of [[Keith Marischal]] in 1589, and also constructed new buildings at Dunnottar Castle. He also built new harbours at [[Peterhead]] and [[Stonehaven]], using Norwegian timber and employing the mason James Mackene. The earl had a fishing boat and house at [[Footdee]] in Aberdeen, as well as a townhouse between the Tolbooth and the Quay.<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, ''A Protestant Lord in James VI's Scotland: George Keith, Fifth Earl Marischal'' (Boydell, 2019), pp. 152-157.</ref> Other houses included \"Gubriell\" near Dunfermline.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 749.</ref>\n\nHe married firstly (c. Feb. 1581) Margaret, the daughter of [[Alexander Home, 5th Lord Home]], by whom he had:\n\n*[[William Keith, 6th Earl Marischal|William, 6th Earl Marischal]].\n*Anne who married [[William Douglas, 7th Earl of Morton]].\n*Margaret who married (as his 1st wife) [[Robert Arbuthnot, 1st Viscount of Arbuthnott|Sir Robert Arbuthnott, of that ilk]] but had no issue.\n*Mary Keith married John Campbell of Cawdor\n\nHe married secondly (c. 1599), Margaret daughter of James Ogilvy, 6th [[Earl of Airlie|Lord Ogilvy of Airlie]], by whom he had:\n\n*James Keith of Benholm who had no male issue.\n*John Keith who had no issue.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*''A Genealogical History of the Dormant, Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire'', Sir Bernard Burke, 1883.\n*{{ODNBweb|id=15263|title=Keith, George, fourth Earl Marischal}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|sc}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lord High Commissioner to the Parliament of Scotland|Lord High Commissioner]]|years=1609\u20131617|before=[[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|The Duke of Lennox]]|after=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|The Marquess of Hamilton]]}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box | before=[[William Keith, 4th Earl Marischal|William Keith]] | title=[[Earl Marischal]] | after=[[William Keith, 6th Earl Marischal|William Keith]] | years=1581\u20131623}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marischal, George Keith, 5th Earl}}\n[[Category:1623 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Scotland to Denmark]]\n[[Category:Earls Marischal]]\n[[Category:Founders of Scottish schools and colleges]]\n[[Category:Lords High Commissioner to the Parliament of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Aberdeen]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Keith,_5th_Earl_Marischal"}
{"title_page": "Animal Headdress", "text_new": "{{Infobox monarch\n| name =Animal Headdress\n| title =Ajaw of [[Tikal]]\n| image =Animal Headdress.svg\n| image_size =150px\n| caption =Animal Headdress's glyph\n| reign =c.290\n| coronation =\n| full name = \n| predecessor =[[Foliated Jaguar]]\n| successor =[[Sihyaj Chan K'awiil I]]\n| spouse  =Lady Skull\n| issue =Sihyaj Chan K'awiil I\n| royal house =\n| father =\n| mother =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| date of burial =\n| place of burial =\n| religion= [[Maya religion]] \n|\n}}\n\n'''Animal Headdress''',<ref group=\"N\">The ruler's name, when transcribed is '''? K'INICH-E:B-?''', Martin & Grube 2008, p.26.</ref> (fl. c. 292) was ''[[ajaw]]'' (\"lord\") of the [[maya civilization|Maya]] city-state of [[Tikal]]. He was father of his successor [[Sihyaj Chan K'awiil I]] and husband of Lady Skull.<ref>Martin & Grube 2008, pp.26-27.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}<!--BEGIN biblio format. If indent param. is used,  Pls use a colon (:) instead of asterisk (*) for bullet markers in the references list -->\n:{{cite book|author=Martin, Simon|authorlink=Simon Martin (Mayanist)|author2=[[Nikolai Grube]]|year=2008|title=Chronicle of the Maya Kings and Queens: Deciphering the Dynasties of the Ancient Maya|location=London and New York|publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]]|edition=2nd|isbn=9780500287262|oclc=191753193}}\n{{refend}}<!-- END biblio format style -->\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Rulers of Tikal|''Ajaw'' of Tikal]]|before=[[Foliated Jaguar]]|after=[[Sihyaj Chan K'awiil I]]|years=c.290}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Tikal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Animal Headdress}}\n[[Category:Rulers of Tikal]]\n[[Category:3rd century in the Maya civilization]]\n[[Category:3rd-century monarchs in North America]]\n\n\n{{Mesoamerica-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox monarch\n| name =Animal Headdress\n| title =