{"title_page": "Columbia Sportswear", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n |name         = Columbia Sportswear Company\n |logo         = [[File:Columbia Sportswear Co logo.svg|200px|Columbia Sportswear logo]] \n |type         = [[Public company|Public]]\n |traded_as    = {{NASDAQ|COLM}}<br>[[S&P 400]] component<br>[[Russell 1000 Index]] component\n |foundation   = {{start date and age|1938}}\n |location     = [[Washington County, Oregon]] (near [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]), <br>[[United States]]<br>{{coord|45.52938|-122.82535|type:edu_source:googlemaps_region:US-OR|display=inline,title}} <!-- geocoded street address -->\n |locations    = 129 (December 2017)<ref>[http://investor.columbia.com/static-files/96c1135d-c560-4ed1-8a7c-b6b7fdbdaa0d Columbia Sportswear Company 2017 Annual Report]</ref>\n |key_people   = [[Timothy Boyle]] {{small|([[Chief executive officer|CEO]] and Acting Chairman)}}<ref name=\"tim boyle acting chairman\"/><br>Thomas Cusick ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])\n |num_employees= 8,900 (Dec 2019) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/columbia-sportswear |title= Columbia Sportswear Company Profile |accessdate= April 9, 2020 |publisher= Craft}}</ref>\n |industry     = [[Apparel]]\n | brands = Columbia<br/>[[Sorel (brand)|Sorel]]<br/>[[Mountain Hardwear]]<br/>[[prAna]]\n |revenue      = [[United States dollar|US$]]2.8 billion (2018)\n |products     = Outerwear and [[sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]]\n |homepage     = [https://www.columbia.com/ www.columbia.com]\n}}\n[[File:HK Quarry Bay Taikoo Shing Cityplaza Columbia Sportswear Co Shop.JPG|thumb|Columbia Sportswear retail store in [[Hong Kong]]]]\n\nThe '''Columbia Sportswear Company''' is a company that manufactures and distributes [[outerwear]], [[sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]], and [[footwear]], as well as [[headgear]], [[camping|camping equipment]], [[skiwear|ski apparel]], and outerwear [[Accessory (fashion)|accessories]].\n\nIt was founded in 1938 by Paul Lamfrom, the father of [[Gert Boyle]]. The company is headquartered in [[Cedar Mill, Oregon|Cedar Mill]], an [[unincorporated area]] in [[Washington County, Oregon]], in the [[Portland metropolitan area]] near [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]].\n\nColumbia's rapid sales growth was fueled by its jackets, which featured breathable waterproof fabric and interchangeable shells and liners.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\n==History==\nColumbia Sportswear began as a family-owned hat distributor. Immediate-past chairwoman [[Gert Boyle]]'s parents, Paul and Marie Lamfrom, fled [[Nazi Germany]] in 1937 and immediately purchased a Portland hat distributorship. The company became Columbia Hat Company, named for the nearby [[Columbia River]]. In 1948, Gert married Neal Boyle, who became the head of the company. Frustrations over suppliers influenced the family to start manufacturing their own products, and Columbia Hat Company became Columbia Sportswear Company in 1960.<ref name=\"milestones\">{{cite web|title=Columbia Milestones|publisher=Columbia Sportswear|url=http://www.columbia.com/history/About_Us_History,default,pg.html|accessdate=2009-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109165956/http://www.columbia.com/history/About_Us_History,default,pg.html|archive-date=2013-11-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, Neal Boyle died following a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. Gert and son Tim Boyle, then a [[University of Oregon]] senior, took over the operations of Columbia, rescuing it from bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/timothy-boyle/|title=Timothy Boyle|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en}}</ref> Gert Boyle served as company president from 1970 until 1988 and additionally became chairman of its board of directors in 1983.<ref name=ImmigrantEntre>{{cite journal|last=Accettola|first=Anna|title=Gertrude Boyle|journal=Immigrant Entrepreneurship: German-American Business Biographies, 1720 to the Present|volume=5|date=October 16, 2012<!-- (updated June 13, 2014)-->|accessdate=November 3, 2019|editor1-first=R. Daniel|editor1-last=Wadhwani|publisher=German Historical Institute|url=http://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=128|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503145450/https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=128|archivedate=May 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> She remained chairman until her death in 2019.<ref name=\"announces passing\">{{cite press release |title=Columbia Sportswear Company Announces the Passing of Gert Boyle |url=https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/275/columbia-sportswear-company-announces-the-passing-of-gert |publisher=Columbia Sportswear |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105105757/https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/275/columbia-sportswear-company-announces-the-passing-of-gert |archivedate=November 5, 2019 |date=November 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Tim Boyle succeeded his mother as Columbia's president and CEO in 1988 and continues to hold the position in 2019.<ref name=\"management team\">{{cite press release |title=Management Team |url=https://investor.columbia.com/company-information/management-team |publisher=Columbia Sportswear |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |date=2019 }}</ref>\n\nColumbia became a [[public company|publicly traded company]] in 1998.<ref name=oreg-2015apr10/><ref>{{cite news \n  | last = Binole\n  | first = Gina\n  | title = Columbia goes public in top-of-the-line style\n  | work = [[Portland Business Journal]]\n  | date = April 3, 1998\n  | url = http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/1998/04/06/story8.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-11-28\n}}</ref> It acquired footwear maker [[Sorel (brand)|Sorel]] in 2000 and [[Mountain Hardwear]] in 2003. In 2006, Columbia acquired the ''Pacific Trail''<ref>{{cite news \n  | title = Columbia Sportswear now owns Pacific Trail\n  | work= [[Portland Business Journal]]\n  | date = March 30, 2006\n  | url = http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/03/27/daily21.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-11-28\n}}</ref> and [[Columbia Montrail|Montrail]] brands,<ref name=oreg-2015apr10/><ref>{{cite news \n  | title = Columbia Sportswear buys Montrail\n  | work = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n  | date = January 27, 2006\n  | url = http://www.seattlepi.com/business/257238_montrail27.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-11-28\n}}</ref> and in 2014 they acquired [[Prana (brand)|prAna]].\n\n[[File:Columbia Sportswear headquarters - Cedar Mill, Oregon.jpg|thumb|Columbia Sportswear's company headquarters in [[Washington County, Oregon]]]]\n\nIn 2001, the company moved its headquarters from [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] to a site in an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] part of [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]],<ref name=\"stayingput\">{{cite news|last=Dworkin|first=Andy|title=Columbia Sportswear staying put|date= August 30, 2007| work=[[The Oregonian]] |url= http://blog.oregonlive.com/breakingnews/2007/08/columbia_sportswear_staying_pu.html |accessdate=2009-11-28}}</ref> in the [[Cedar Mill, Oregon|Cedar Mill]] area and just outside the [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]] city limits.  The site on NW&nbsp;Science Park Drive has a Portland mailing address, but is not in Portland.  In 2007, City of Portland officials attempted to convince Columbia Sportswear to move back to Portland,<ref>{{cite news |title=Columbia's 'tough mother' squashes return rumor |work=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date = March 3, 2007 |url= http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/03/05/newscolumn4.html |accessdate=2009-11-28}}</ref> but the company ultimately rejected the idea due to the increased corporate tax burden such a move would entail and decided to expand its existing headquarters instead.<ref name=\"stayingput\"/>\n\nIn 2001, it was the largest American retailer of ski apparel based on [[gross revenue]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Senior |first=Jeanie |title=Seamless warehouse is a marvel |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=November 9, 2001 |url= http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=7713 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110608055446/http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=7713 |archivedate= June 8, 2011 |accessdate = 2015-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2008, Columbia Sportswear announced a three-year sponsorship of the cycling team formerly known as ''Team High Road'' and before that ''T-Mobile'' and ''Team Telekom''.  The sponsorship began on July 5, 2008 with the start of the [[2008 Tour de France|Tour de France]]. The team's name was \"[[Team Columbia]]\". The sponsorship included both the men's and women's teams, and ended at the end of 2010.<ref>{{cite press\n |title=Columbia Sportswear Announces Sponsorship \n |publisher=Team Columbia & High Road Sports, Inc \n |date=June 15, 2008 \n |url=http://www.highroadsports.com/news/173-Columbia-Sportswear-Company-and-High-Road-Sports-Announce-New-Team-Columbia-to-Debut-at-2008-Tour-de-France \n |accessdate=2008-06-17 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620054345/http://www.highroadsports.com/news/173-Columbia-Sportswear-Company-and-High-Road-Sports-Announce-New-Team-Columbia-to-Debut-at-2008-Tour-de-France \n |archivedate=2008-06-20 \n}}</ref>\n\nOn August 4, 2010, Columbia Sportswear Company signed an agreement to acquire OutDry Technologies S.r.l., which owns the intellectual property and other assets comprising the OutDry brand and related business, via a cash purchase from Nextec S.r.l., based near Milan, Italy. The transaction was expected to close during the third quarter of 2010, subject to customary closing conditions, and is not expected to have a material effect on the company's 2010 operating results.<ref>{{cite press\n | title = Columbia Sportswear Company to Acquire OutDry Technologies S.r.l.\n | publisher = BUSINESS WIRE\n | date = August 4, 2010\n | url = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100804005135/en/Columbia-Sportswear-Company-Acquire-OutDry%C2%AE-Technologies-S.r.l.\n | accessdate = 2010-08-10\n}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Bryan Timm was named president of the company, taking over that position from Tim Boyle, who remained CEO.<ref name=oreg-2015apr10>{{cite news|last=Brettman|first=Allan|title=Columbia charts its next billion dollars<!--(print-edition headline)-->|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=April 10, 2015|page=C1|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/playbooks-profits/index.ssf/2015/04/columbia_sportswear_sets_sight.html|accessdate=2015-04-15}}</ref>  In May 2017 it was announced Timm would step down and the duties of president would revert to Tim Boyle.<ref>https://fashionunited.com/news/people/columbia-sportswear-company-s-coo-bryan-timm-steps-down/2017051715881</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2019, chairwoman [[Gert Boyle]] died at the age of 95.<ref name=\"obit-oregonian\">{{cite news |last=Duin |first=Steve |title=Gert Boyle, longtime Columbia Sportswear chairwoman, dies at 95 |date=November 3, 2019 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url= https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2019/11/gert-boyle-longtime-columbia-sportswear-chairwoman-dies-at-95.html |accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref> Tim Boyle was named as Acting Chairman of the company's board of directors.<ref name=\"tim boyle acting chairman\">{{cite press release |title=Tim Boyle to Serve as Acting Chairman of Columbia Sportswear Company\u2019s Board of Directors Following the Passing of Gert Boyle; Details Regarding Share Ownership |url=https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/276/tim-boyle-to-serve-as-acting-chairman-of-columbia|publisher=Columbia Sportswear |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105110523/https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/276/tim-boyle-to-serve-as-acting-chairman-of-columbia |archivedate=November 5, 2019 |date=November 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\n[[Image:ColumbiaSportswearStore.JPG|thumb|Columbia's flagship store in downtown [[Portland, Oregon]]]]\nColumbia Sportswear distributes its products in more than 72 countries and 13,000 retailers. Columbia also operates its own chain of retail stores, including its flagship store located in [[downtown Portland]], Oregon.\n\n==Financial information==\nAs of February 12, 2015, the company's [[market capitalization]] is about $4.13 billion,{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} with 2014 net sales of $2.1 billion.<ref name=oreg-2015apr10/>\n\nAs of 2018, 40% of Columbia's business came from abroad.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\n===Stock exchanges===\nColumbia Sportswear Company is publicly traded on [[NASDAQ]] with ticker symbol COLM.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/COLM/|title=COLM : Summary for Columbia Sportswear Company - Yahoo Finance|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\n===Trade and tariffs===\nThe clothing business in the US is still largely subject to what remains of the [[Smoot\u2013Hawley Tariff Act]], passed in 1930. Since 2001, Columbia has paired its designers with teams of [[trade|trade experts]] in a process the company calls \"[[tariff]] engineering\" in order to reach lower tariffs, [[tax|taxes]], or [[duty|duties]]. For example, Columbia applies a very thin layer of fabric to the [[sole (shoe)|soles]] of its shoes since tariffs on fabric soles are lower than those on rubber soles; the fabric wears away within days.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\">{{cite web |last1=Tankersley |first1=Jim |title=A Winter-Coat Heavyweight Gives Trump\u2019s Trade War the Cold Shoulder |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/23/business/economy/columbia-sportswear-trump-trade-war.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> For similar reasons, jackets are [[waterproofing|waterproofed]] and filled with at least 10% [[down feather|down]].\n\n[[Vietnam]] is Columbia's largest supplier, and 25% of the company's footwear originates in [[China]].<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\nColumbia has operated in China since 2014 as Columbia Sportswear Commercial (Shanghai) Company as a joint venture with [[Swire Pacific Limited]], reaching a total of 86 Chinese retail stores by 2017.<ref name=\"acquire\">{{cite web |title=Columbia Sportswear Company Announces Intention to Acquire Remaining Interest in China Joint Venture from Swire Resources Limited |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180410006756/en/Columbia-Sportswear-Company-Announces-Intention-Acquire-Remaining |website=Business Wire |accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Columbia announced it would buy out Swire's remaining 40% stake by 2019.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n* [[List of companies based in Oregon]]\n*[[List of outdoor industry parent companies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Columbia Sportswear Company}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.columbia.com/}}\n\n{{ORCompanies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Outdoor clothing brands]]\n[[Category:Sportswear brands]]\n[[Category:Sporting goods retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Shoe brands]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of the United States]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Cedar Mill, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Mountaineering equipment manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Eyewear brands of the United States]]\n[[Category:1998 initial public offerings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n |name         = Columbia Sportswear Company\n |logo         = [[File:Columbia Sportswear Co logo.svg|200px|Columbia Sportswear logo]] \n |type         = [[Public company|Public]]\n |traded_as    = {{NASDAQ|COLM}}<br>[[S&P 400]] component<br>[[Russell 1000 Index]] component\n |foundation   = {{start date and age|1938}}\n |location     = [[Washington County, Oregon]] (near [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]]), <br>[[United States]]<br>{{coord|45.52938|-122.82535|type:edu_source:googlemaps_region:US-OR|display=inline,title}} <!-- geocoded street address -->\n |locations    = 129 (December 2017)<ref>[http://investor.columbia.com/static-files/96c1135d-c560-4ed1-8a7c-b6b7fdbdaa0d Columbia Sportswear Company 2017 Annual Report]</ref>\n |key_people   = [[Timothy Boyle]] {{small|([[Chief executive officer|CEO]] and Acting Chairman)}}<ref name=\"tim boyle acting chairman\"/><br>Thomas Cusick ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])\n |num_employees= 6,511 (2018) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://craft.co/columbia-sportswear |title= Columbia Sportswear Company Profile |accessdate= August 30, 2019 |publisher= Craft}}</ref>\n |industry     = [[Apparel]]\n | brands = Columbia<br/>[[Sorel (brand)|Sorel]]<br/>[[Mountain Hardwear]]<br/>[[prAna]]\n |revenue      = [[United States dollar|US$]]2.8 billion (2018)\n |products     = Outerwear and [[sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]]\n |homepage     = [https://www.columbia.com/ www.columbia.com]\n}}\n[[File:HK Quarry Bay Taikoo Shing Cityplaza Columbia Sportswear Co Shop.JPG|thumb|Columbia Sportswear retail store in [[Hong Kong]]]]\n\nThe '''Columbia Sportswear Company''' is a company that manufactures and distributes [[outerwear]], [[sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]], and [[footwear]], as well as [[headgear]], [[camping|camping equipment]], [[skiwear|ski apparel]], and outerwear [[Accessory (fashion)|accessories]].\n\nIt was founded in 1938 by Paul Lamfrom, the father of [[Gert Boyle]]. The company is headquartered in [[Cedar Mill, Oregon|Cedar Mill]], an [[unincorporated area]] in [[Washington County, Oregon]], in the [[Portland metropolitan area]] near [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]].\n\nColumbia's rapid sales growth was fueled by its jackets, which featured breathable waterproof fabric and interchangeable shells and liners.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\n==History==\nColumbia Sportswear began as a family-owned hat distributor. Immediate-past chairwoman [[Gert Boyle]]'s parents, Paul and Marie Lamfrom, fled [[Nazi Germany]] in 1937 and immediately purchased a Portland hat distributorship. The company became Columbia Hat Company, named for the nearby [[Columbia River]]. In 1948, Gert married Neal Boyle, who became the head of the company. Frustrations over suppliers influenced the family to start manufacturing their own products, and Columbia Hat Company became Columbia Sportswear Company in 1960.<ref name=\"milestones\">{{cite web|title=Columbia Milestones|publisher=Columbia Sportswear|url=http://www.columbia.com/history/About_Us_History,default,pg.html|accessdate=2009-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109165956/http://www.columbia.com/history/About_Us_History,default,pg.html|archive-date=2013-11-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, Neal Boyle died following a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. Gert and son Tim Boyle, then a [[University of Oregon]] senior, took over the operations of Columbia, rescuing it from bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/timothy-boyle/|title=Timothy Boyle|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en}}</ref> Gert Boyle served as company president from 1970 until 1988 and additionally became chairman of its board of directors in 1983.<ref name=ImmigrantEntre>{{cite journal|last=Accettola|first=Anna|title=Gertrude Boyle|journal=Immigrant Entrepreneurship: German-American Business Biographies, 1720 to the Present|volume=5|date=October 16, 2012<!-- (updated June 13, 2014)-->|accessdate=November 3, 2019|editor1-first=R. Daniel|editor1-last=Wadhwani|publisher=German Historical Institute|url=http://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=128|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503145450/https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entry.php?rec=128|archivedate=May 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> She remained chairman until her death in 2019.<ref name=\"announces passing\">{{cite press release |title=Columbia Sportswear Company Announces the Passing of Gert Boyle |url=https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/275/columbia-sportswear-company-announces-the-passing-of-gert |publisher=Columbia Sportswear |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105105757/https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/275/columbia-sportswear-company-announces-the-passing-of-gert |archivedate=November 5, 2019 |date=November 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Tim Boyle succeeded his mother as Columbia's president and CEO in 1988 and continues to hold the position in 2019.<ref name=\"management team\">{{cite press release |title=Management Team |url=https://investor.columbia.com/company-information/management-team |publisher=Columbia Sportswear |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |date=2019 }}</ref>\n\nColumbia became a [[public company|publicly traded company]] in 1998.<ref name=oreg-2015apr10/><ref>{{cite news \n  | last = Binole\n  | first = Gina\n  | title = Columbia goes public in top-of-the-line style\n  | work = [[Portland Business Journal]]\n  | date = April 3, 1998\n  | url = http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/1998/04/06/story8.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-11-28\n}}</ref> It acquired footwear maker [[Sorel (brand)|Sorel]] in 2000 and [[Mountain Hardwear]] in 2003. In 2006, Columbia acquired the ''Pacific Trail''<ref>{{cite news \n  | title = Columbia Sportswear now owns Pacific Trail\n  | work= [[Portland Business Journal]]\n  | date = March 30, 2006\n  | url = http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/03/27/daily21.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-11-28\n}}</ref> and [[Columbia Montrail|Montrail]] brands,<ref name=oreg-2015apr10/><ref>{{cite news \n  | title = Columbia Sportswear buys Montrail\n  | work = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n  | date = January 27, 2006\n  | url = http://www.seattlepi.com/business/257238_montrail27.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-11-28\n}}</ref> and in 2014 they acquired [[Prana (brand)|prAna]].\n\n[[File:Columbia Sportswear headquarters - Cedar Mill, Oregon.jpg|thumb|Columbia Sportswear's company headquarters in [[Washington County, Oregon]]]]\n\nIn 2001, the company moved its headquarters from [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] to a site in an [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] part of [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]],<ref name=\"stayingput\">{{cite news|last=Dworkin|first=Andy|title=Columbia Sportswear staying put|date= August 30, 2007| work=[[The Oregonian]] |url= http://blog.oregonlive.com/breakingnews/2007/08/columbia_sportswear_staying_pu.html |accessdate=2009-11-28}}</ref> in the [[Cedar Mill, Oregon|Cedar Mill]] area and just outside the [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]] city limits.  The site on NW&nbsp;Science Park Drive has a Portland mailing address, but is not in Portland.  In 2007, City of Portland officials attempted to convince Columbia Sportswear to move back to Portland,<ref>{{cite news |title=Columbia's 'tough mother' squashes return rumor |work=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date = March 3, 2007 |url= http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/03/05/newscolumn4.html |accessdate=2009-11-28}}</ref> but the company ultimately rejected the idea due to the increased corporate tax burden such a move would entail and decided to expand its existing headquarters instead.<ref name=\"stayingput\"/>\n\nIn 2001, it was the largest American retailer of ski apparel based on [[gross revenue]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Senior |first=Jeanie |title=Seamless warehouse is a marvel |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=November 9, 2001 |url= http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=7713 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110608055446/http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=7713 |archivedate= June 8, 2011 |accessdate = 2015-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2008, Columbia Sportswear announced a three-year sponsorship of the cycling team formerly known as ''Team High Road'' and before that ''T-Mobile'' and ''Team Telekom''.  The sponsorship began on July 5, 2008 with the start of the [[2008 Tour de France|Tour de France]]. The team's name was \"[[Team Columbia]]\". The sponsorship included both the men's and women's teams, and ended at the end of 2010.<ref>{{cite press\n |title=Columbia Sportswear Announces Sponsorship \n |publisher=Team Columbia & High Road Sports, Inc \n |date=June 15, 2008 \n |url=http://www.highroadsports.com/news/173-Columbia-Sportswear-Company-and-High-Road-Sports-Announce-New-Team-Columbia-to-Debut-at-2008-Tour-de-France \n |accessdate=2008-06-17 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620054345/http://www.highroadsports.com/news/173-Columbia-Sportswear-Company-and-High-Road-Sports-Announce-New-Team-Columbia-to-Debut-at-2008-Tour-de-France \n |archivedate=2008-06-20 \n}}</ref>\n\nOn August 4, 2010, Columbia Sportswear Company signed an agreement to acquire OutDry Technologies S.r.l., which owns the intellectual property and other assets comprising the OutDry brand and related business, via a cash purchase from Nextec S.r.l., based near Milan, Italy. The transaction was expected to close during the third quarter of 2010, subject to customary closing conditions, and is not expected to have a material effect on the company's 2010 operating results.<ref>{{cite press\n | title = Columbia Sportswear Company to Acquire OutDry Technologies S.r.l.\n | publisher = BUSINESS WIRE\n | date = August 4, 2010\n | url = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100804005135/en/Columbia-Sportswear-Company-Acquire-OutDry%C2%AE-Technologies-S.r.l.\n | accessdate = 2010-08-10\n}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Bryan Timm was named president of the company, taking over that position from Tim Boyle, who remained CEO.<ref name=oreg-2015apr10>{{cite news|last=Brettman|first=Allan|title=Columbia charts its next billion dollars<!--(print-edition headline)-->|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=April 10, 2015|page=C1|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/playbooks-profits/index.ssf/2015/04/columbia_sportswear_sets_sight.html|accessdate=2015-04-15}}</ref>  In May 2017 it was announced Timm would step down and the duties of president would revert to Tim Boyle.<ref>https://fashionunited.com/news/people/columbia-sportswear-company-s-coo-bryan-timm-steps-down/2017051715881</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2019, chairwoman [[Gert Boyle]] died at the age of 95.<ref name=\"obit-oregonian\">{{cite news |last=Duin |first=Steve |title=Gert Boyle, longtime Columbia Sportswear chairwoman, dies at 95 |date=November 3, 2019 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url= https://www.oregonlive.com/news/2019/11/gert-boyle-longtime-columbia-sportswear-chairwoman-dies-at-95.html |accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref> Tim Boyle was named as Acting Chairman of the company's board of directors.<ref name=\"tim boyle acting chairman\">{{cite press release |title=Tim Boyle to Serve as Acting Chairman of Columbia Sportswear Company\u2019s Board of Directors Following the Passing of Gert Boyle; Details Regarding Share Ownership |url=https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/276/tim-boyle-to-serve-as-acting-chairman-of-columbia|publisher=Columbia Sportswear |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105110523/https://investor.columbia.com/news-events/press-releases/detail/276/tim-boyle-to-serve-as-acting-chairman-of-columbia |archivedate=November 5, 2019 |date=November 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\n[[Image:ColumbiaSportswearStore.JPG|thumb|Columbia's flagship store in downtown [[Portland, Oregon]]]]\nColumbia Sportswear distributes its products in more than 72 countries and 13,000 retailers. Columbia also operates its own chain of retail stores, including its flagship store located in [[downtown Portland]], Oregon.\n\n==Financial information==\nAs of February 12, 2015, the company's [[market capitalization]] is about $4.13 billion,{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} with 2014 net sales of $2.1 billion.<ref name=oreg-2015apr10/>\n\nAs of 2018, 40% of Columbia's business came from abroad.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\n===Stock exchanges===\nColumbia Sportswear Company is publicly traded on [[NASDAQ]] with ticker symbol COLM.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/COLM/|title=COLM : Summary for Columbia Sportswear Company - Yahoo Finance|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\n===Trade and tariffs===\nThe clothing business in the US is still largely subject to what remains of the [[Smoot\u2013Hawley Tariff Act]], passed in 1930. Since 2001, Columbia has paired its designers with teams of [[trade|trade experts]] in a process the company calls \"[[tariff]] engineering\" in order to reach lower tariffs, [[tax|taxes]], or [[duty|duties]]. For example, Columbia applies a very thin layer of fabric to the [[sole (shoe)|soles]] of its shoes since tariffs on fabric soles are lower than those on rubber soles; the fabric wears away within days.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\">{{cite web |last1=Tankersley |first1=Jim |title=A Winter-Coat Heavyweight Gives Trump\u2019s Trade War the Cold Shoulder |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/23/business/economy/columbia-sportswear-trump-trade-war.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> For similar reasons, jackets are [[waterproofing|waterproofed]] and filled with at least 10% [[down feather|down]].\n\n[[Vietnam]] is Columbia's largest supplier, and 25% of the company's footwear originates in [[China]].<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\nColumbia has operated in China since 2014 as Columbia Sportswear Commercial (Shanghai) Company as a joint venture with [[Swire Pacific Limited]], reaching a total of 86 Chinese retail stores by 2017.<ref name=\"acquire\">{{cite web |title=Columbia Sportswear Company Announces Intention to Acquire Remaining Interest in China Joint Venture from Swire Resources Limited |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180410006756/en/Columbia-Sportswear-Company-Announces-Intention-Acquire-Remaining |website=Business Wire |accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Columbia announced it would buy out Swire's remaining 40% stake by 2019.<ref name=\"nyt-11-18\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n* [[List of companies based in Oregon]]\n*[[List of outdoor industry parent companies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Columbia Sportswear Company}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.columbia.com/}}\n\n{{ORCompanies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies established in 1938]]\n[[Category:Outdoor clothing brands]]\n[[Category:Sportswear brands]]\n[[Category:Sporting goods retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Shoe brands]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of the United States]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Cedar Mill, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Mountaineering equipment manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Eyewear brands of the United States]]\n[[Category:1998 initial public offerings]]\n", "name_user": "Lukehammer", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated employee count from same source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Columbia_Sportswear"}
